TY  - JOUR
T1  - Identifying Agglomeration Spillovers: Evidence from Winners and Losers of Large Plant Openings
AU  - Greenstone, Michael
AU  - Hornbeck, Richard
AU  - Moretti, Enrico
Y1  - 2010/06/01
PY  - 2010
DA  - 2010/06/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/653714
DO  - 10.1086/653714
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 536
EP  - 598
VL  - 118
IS  - 3
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - We quantify agglomeration spillovers by comparing changes in total factor productivity (TFP) among incumbent plants in ?winning? counties that attracted a large manufacturing plant and ?losing? counties that were the new plant's runner?up choice. Winning and losing counties have similar trends in TFP prior to the new plant opening. Five years after the opening, incumbent plants' TFP is 12 percent higher in winning counties. This productivity spillover is larger for plants sharing similar labor and technology pools with the new plant. Consistent with spatial equilibrium models, labor costs increase in winning counties, indicating that profits ultimately increase less than productivity.
AB  - We quantify agglomeration spillovers by comparing changes in total factor productivity (TFP) among incumbent plants in ?winning? counties that attracted a large manufacturing plant and ?losing? counties that were the new plant's runner?up choice. Winning and losing counties have similar trends in TFP prior to the new plant opening. Five years after the opening, incumbent plants' TFP is 12 percent higher in winning counties. This productivity spillover is larger for plants sharing similar labor and technology pools with the new plant. Consistent with spatial equilibrium models, labor costs increase in winning counties, indicating that profits ultimately increase less than productivity.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/653714
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/653714
Y2  - 2024/03/20
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - Competition and the Structure of Vertical Relationships in Capital Markets
AU  - Asker, John
AU  - Ljungqvist, Alexander
Y1  - 2010/06/01
PY  - 2010
DA  - 2010/06/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/653452
DO  - 10.1086/653452
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 599
EP  - 647
VL  - 118
IS  - 3
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - We show that information flows between investment banks and their clients affect relationships and that shocks to these flows affect corporate investment. Firms avoid sharing investment banks in their industry, but only when they engage in product market competition. This suggests that concerns about disclosure of confidential information to strategic rivals determine firms? investment bank choices. Using exogenous shocks to information flows arising from bank mergers, we show that the desire to avoid sharing banks has a substantial effect on investment. These information effects help us understand how the investment banking industry is structured, how banks compete, and how prices are set.
AB  - We show that information flows between investment banks and their clients affect relationships and that shocks to these flows affect corporate investment. Firms avoid sharing investment banks in their industry, but only when they engage in product market competition. This suggests that concerns about disclosure of confidential information to strategic rivals determine firms? investment bank choices. Using exogenous shocks to information flows arising from bank mergers, we show that the desire to avoid sharing banks has a substantial effect on investment. These information effects help us understand how the investment banking industry is structured, how banks compete, and how prices are set.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/653452
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/653452
Y2  - 2024/03/20
ER  - 

